## SOLID Principles

| Principle | Rule |
|-----------|------|
| **S** ingle Responsibility | Every class has exactly **one reason to change** |
| **O** pen/Closed | Classes are **open for extension, closed for modification** — add behaviour by subclassing or composing, not by editing existing code |
| **L** iskov Substitution | Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types |
| **I** nterface Segregation | Prefer **many small, focused interfaces** over one fat interface |
| **D** ependency Inversion | High-level modules depend on **abstractions**, not on concrete low-level details |

---

## Class Design

- Class names are **nouns** (`OrderProcessor`, `UserRepository`); method names are **verbs** (`processOrder`, `findById`)
- A class should fit comfortably in one screen (~200–300 lines); split larger classes
- Constructors should only **initialise state**, not perform complex logic or I/O
- Use **factory methods or builder patterns** for complex object creation
- Implement `equals`/`hashCode` (or `__eq__`/`__hash__`) consistently whenever objects are compared or used in hash-based collections
- Make classes **final/sealed** unless they are explicitly designed for extension

## Method Design

- Methods do **one thing only**; if you need "and" to describe it, split it
- Keep methods **short** (ideally ≤ 20 lines); extract helpers aggressively
- Limit parameters to **≤ 3–4**; group related params into a value object
- Return **early** to avoid deep nesting (guard clauses)
- Avoid side-effects in query methods (Command-Query Separation)

---

## Error Handling

- Use **typed exceptions/result types** for expected failure modes; avoid returning `null` or magic values
- Catch exceptions at the **right level** — only where you can meaningfully handle them
- Never swallow exceptions silently (`catch (Exception e) {}`)
- Clean up resources with `try-with-resources`, `using`, or context managers

## Immutability & State

- Prefer **immutable value objects** for domain concepts (money, coordinates, dates)
- Mark fields `final` / `readonly` / `val` wherever they should not change after construction
- Minimise shared mutable state; prefer passing data explicitly

## Dependencies & Coupling

- Use **dependency injection** — objects receive their collaborators, they don't create them
- Depend on **abstractions** (interfaces/protocols), not concrete classes
- Avoid static state and singleton abuse; they create hidden coupling and hinder testing

## Testing

- Design every class to be **independently testable** (no hidden globals, no hard-coded dependencies)
- One test class per production class; test behaviour, not implementation details
- Use **mocks/stubs only for boundaries** (I/O, network, DB) — not for every collaborator

---

## Naming Conventions (language-agnostic)

- Classes: `PascalCase`
- Methods / functions: `camelCase` (Java/C#/JS) or `snake_case` (Python)
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Interfaces: prefix with `I` only where the language convention demands it (C#); otherwise plain noun (`Serializable`, `Repository`)
- Booleans: name as predicates (`isActive`, `hasPermission`, `canRetry`)

## Code Smells to Avoid

- **God Class** — knows and does too much
- **Feature Envy** — a method more interested in another class's data than its own
- **Data Class** — a class with only fields and no behaviour
- **Long Parameter List** — introduce a parameter object
- **Primitive Obsession** — wrap domain concepts (e.g. `EmailAddress`) instead of passing raw strings/ints
- **Inappropriate Intimacy** — classes accessing each other's private internals
- **Divergent Change / Shotgun Surgery** — signs that responsibilities are misallocated
